Introduction

New York City is known for being among the most expensive cities in the world to live in, and not to mention in regard to buying the real estate properties. The property market in Manhattan, out of the seven boroughs of NYC have long been, undoubtedly, the most pricey and the most sought-after one. The purpose of this market analysis is to find out answers to questions: is there any variable that would largely determine the sale prices of the properties? If not, what variables would significantly influence the sale price; what variables do not have much impact on the finalization of the sale price?

Data Source

This report is based on the rolling sales dataset scraped from NYC Governments Department of Finance. The latest update of this dataset was in November 2019.
https://www1.nyc.gov/site/finance/taxes/property-rolling-sales-data.page

Packages

Packages used for coding are listed as follows.
rmdformats: to import the theme pacakge for the markdown file

formattable: to do the data preview section
magrittr: to decrease development time and to improve readability and maintainability of code
knitr: to control the output, for example, by using the kable() functoin
modelr: to model functions
plotly: to plot
corrplot: to draw the correlation plots
pwr: to conduct power analysis
gridExtra: to combine multiple graphs

Data Exploration & Preparation

Data Import and Basic Data Exploration

From dim() function, we could see that this dataset originally includes 17751 observations, and 21 variables.
From the names() function, we could get an idea of how the names of variables are stored - pretty important since there are 21 variables of them and some of them are identical in terms of wording.
From the str() function, we could get the data types for the variables included - and for the ordered factors and factors, the number of levels/classes included.
From the summary() function, we could get an idea of the distribution of variables, and also information such as if there is any NAs and would it be a big issue. 

manhattan <- read_excel("rollingsales_manhattan.xls")

# hide the results of these codes for output purposes
#dim(manhattan)
#names(manhattan)

#summary(manhattan)

Data Cleaning

  1. Borough is labeled as 1 throughout this dataset, which means Manhattan in New York City, and does not necessarily provide any valuable information for this case. Get rid of this column. As there are NAs throughout the columns named EASE-MENT and Apartment Number. Remove these two columns as well.
manhattan <- manhattan %>%
  select(-BOROUGH, -`EASE-MENT`, -`APARTMENT NUMBER`)
  1. The column Building Class Category has the category number and title merged together in one cell - split this column into two columns as Building Class Category Num and Building Class Category.
manhattan <- manhattan %>%
  separate(col = "BUILDING CLASS CATEGORY", into = c("BUILDING CLASS CATEGORY NUM", "BUILDING CLASS CATEGORY"), sep = 3)
  1. Now create a new column called Building Age based on Year Built so as to make the variable Year Built more useful in future endeavor.
manhattan <- manhattan %>%
  mutate(`BUILDING AGE` = 2019 - `YEAR BUILT`)
  1. Check and remove duplicates. From the result, there are 1091 observations duplicates, which would not necessarily take up a big proportion of the size of the original dataset. Remove them. The resulting dataset now contains 16660 observations and 20 variables.
# Check.
#manhattan %>% filter(duplicated(manhattan) == TRUE) %>% nrow()

# Remove.
manhattan <- unique(manhattan)
  1. Type conversions: Year built, Building Class Category, Building Class Category Num, Building class at present, Buidling class at time of sale, Zip code, Tax Class at Present, and Tax Class at time of sale should be factor; Block, Lot, and Zipcode should be in chr format; Sale Date should be in date format so as to have more practical utility.
# Convert to factors. 
fct <- c(2,3,4,7,9,15,16,17)
manhattan %<>% mutate_at(fct, funs(as.factor(.)))

# Convert to characters.
chr <- c(5,6,9)
manhattan %<>% mutate_at(chr, funs(as.character(.)))

# Convert to date.
manhattan$`SALE DATE` <- ymd(manhattan$`SALE DATE`)
  1. As for the missing values, check how many NAs are included in each column at the moment. From the result, we could see that Tax class at present, Building class at present, Zip code, Year built, and interchangebly, Building age contain missing values. Since only five (actually, four) variables contain NAs, remove them.
# Check NA's by column. 
#colSums(is.na(manhattan))

manhattan <- manhattan %>%
  filter(is.na(manhattan$`BUILDING CLASS AT PRESENT`) == FALSE) 

manhattan <- manhattan %>%
  filter(is.na(manhattan$`ZIP CODE`) == FALSE)
  1. Continue to check if there is any 0 values in the numeric entries. First, start by checking the zero value situation in the column Sale Price. The result of 3348 0s is actually quite a big deal. For sure, the 0s in the price column would have meanings - for example, the sales deal would actually be a sort of transfer deal. However, these zeroes taking up quite a large proportion of all the observations (3348/16660~=20.10%) might skew the dataset in further study. Thus, get rid of these zeroes here; meanwhile, create two separate datasets: one dropping the zero sale price entries, and one keeping them. The cleaned version of the dataset to conduct analysis on now contians 13312 observations, which is around 75% of the original dataset - a pretty decent amount.
# Count zeroes in sale price.
# manhattan %>% filter(`SALE PRICE` == 0) %>% nrow()

#Create separate datasets for further study. 
manhattan_allsp <- manhattan %>% filter(manhattan$`SALE PRICE` == 0)

manhattan_clean <- manhattan %>% filter(!manhattan$`SALE PRICE` == 0)
  1. For numeric variables Land square feet and Gross square feet, Also, check if there is any zero in it. The results are: 12274 0s in land square feet, while there are 6582 0s in gross square feet. For definitions of these two terms: gross square feet generally refers to the total square feet of a space, and is often used to calculate the rent. This is an interesting finding. At the moment, leave these two variables as the way they are.
# Check zeroes in land square feet.
#manhattan_clean %>% filter(manhattan_clean$`LAND SQUARE FEET` == 0) %>% nrow()

# Check zeroes in gross square feet.
#manhattan_clean %>% filter(manhattan_clean$`GROSS SQUARE FEET` == 0) %>% nrow()
  1. Plus, for numeric variables residential units, commercial units, and total units - check if they contain zero values. There are many zeroes: 12546 0s in residential units, 12796 0s in commerical units, and 12337 0s in total units. So, no removing would be conducted at this phase for these three variables in case these zeroes would provide insights.
# Check zeroes in land square feet.
#manhattan_clean %>% filter(manhattan_clean$`RESIDENTIAL UNITS` == 0) %>% nrow()

# Check zeroes in gross square feet.
#manhattan_clean %>% filter(manhattan_clean$`COMMERCIAL UNITS` == 0) %>% nrow()

#manhattan_clean %>% filter(manhattan_clean$`TOTAL UNITS` == 0) %>% nrow()
  1. Now deal with the zero values in year built. Since there are not many of them - drop them.
manhattan_clean <- manhattan %>%
  filter(manhattan$`YEAR BUILT` != 0)
  1. Add in a column extracting the month of the year at the time of sale.
manhattan_clean$`SALE MONTH` <- as.factor(months(manhattan_clean$`SALE DATE`))

Visualization

Neighborhood

The most in-demand, the most expensive and the least expensive neighborhoods in Manhattan.

The most in-demand neighborhoods in Manhattan
Properties in the Upper East Side (E 59th St - E 96th St) and Upper West Side (W 59th St - W 96th) are of high demands. This makes sense as properties in these areaes are mainly residential. From common sense, sales of residential properties are considered more frequent compared with sales of properties of other kinds because of the large population that reside in Manhattan; also, some small properties like houses are typically of lower prices compared with the prices of properties like office buildings. Midtown East is also an area that is largely composed on residential buildings. In fact, the top ten neighborhoods listed here are all residential-oriented.

# Most-in-demand neighborhood.
df11 <- manhattan_clean %>%
  group_by(NEIGHBORHOOD) %>%
  summarise(count = n()) %>%
  arrange(desc(count)) %>%
  head(10)

p11 <- ggplot(df11, aes(x = `NEIGHBORHOOD`, y = count)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  coord_flip() +
  ggtitle("Most In-Demand Neighborhoods in Manhattan") +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom") +
  scale_y_continuous("# of Sales", labels = scales::comma) +
  scale_x_discrete("Neighborhood")

p11

The most expensive neighborhoods in Manhattan
Most of the buildings in the top neighborhoods listed here are office buildings, such as the Midtown CBS, Fashion District, and Javits Center. Office buildings are typically of much larger sizes - think about the skyscrapers that dominate throughout Manhattans skyline. So, this result could also be verified through common sense.

# Most expensive neighborhood.
df12 <- manhattan_clean %>%

  summarise(avgSP = mean(`SALE PRICE`)) %>%

The least expensive neighborhoods in Manhattan
Roosevelt Island is actually one of the newly developed areas in Manhattan. In despite of its great potential as more and more residential building projects are under progress, since it still lacks a well-built and well-organized enviroment for living and working, it makes sense that it results as one of the two least expensive neighborhoods.

Building Class Category

The most in-demand, the most expensive and the least expensive building class categories in Manhattan.

The most in-demand building class categories in Manhattan
This result is unsurprising. Due to the large population that Manhattan carries, high-rise apartment buildings are also the most popular ones in Manhattan in regards to real estate. Some interesting findings from this graph are walk-up apartments and condo coops buildings are also of relatively high demands - these two categories are the upcomers in the Manhattan real estate market over these past few years. Many renovated walk up and condo coop buildings are presented in areas with strict regulation in terms of the height of building, such as the Hells Kitchen area around Midtown West.

Tax Class

Tax class at time of sale is a more valuable variable for this report, as it might influence the decision of buying properties to a certain extent.

Tax class at time of sale versus the sale price
Due to the variety of data that this dataset includes, there are quite a lot of outliers that would affect the output of the boxplot. Especially, for tax class 4, the outlier situation is much more pronounced. So, a zoomed-in version of boxplot is created by limiting the range of the y-axis. From the latter graph, we could see that the median sale price for tax class 1 is higher than the medians for tax class 2 and 4. And from a closer look, the median sale price for tax class 4 is slightly lower.

p51 <- ggplot(manhattan_clean, mapping = aes(x = `TAX CLASS AT TIME OF SALE`, y = `SALE PRICE`, fill = `TAX CLASS AT TIME OF SALE`)) +
  geom_boxplot(fill='#A4A4A4', color="black") +
  ggtitle("Sale Prices across Tax Classes", subtitle = "at time of sale") +
  scale_y_continuous("Sale Price", labels = scales::dollar) +
  scale_x_discrete("Tax Class") 

p51

Time Series

This graph is created to see if there is a surge in property deals in terms of time of the year. From the result, some time near Feburary is the time when the market is most active; the second most active periods happen some time around June and July. However, since this graph depicts the result merely from November 2018 to November 2019, there might be concerns that this result is not representative. So, further analysis on this issue is performed in the predictive analysis section.

df6 <- manhattan_clean %>%
  group_by(`SALE DATE`) %>%
  summarise (cbyyear = n())

p6 <- ggplot(df6, mapping = aes(x = `SALE DATE`, y = cbyyear)) +
  geom_line(color = "darkred") +
  ggtitle("Overtime Number of Sales in the Recent Year", subtitle = "Nov 2018 - Nov 2019") +
  scale_y_continuous("# of Sales", labels = scales::comma) +

Correlation

A correlation analysis is conducted to see if there is any collinearity exists among the variables. Since the dataset includes variables of various data types. The correlation analysis is conducted separately for numeric variables and categorical variables. Both a correlation table and a correlation plot are shown as follows.

Correlation between numeric variables

One big finding from this part is that sale price is relatively more correlated to the gross square feet factor, in a positive direction. Plus, the number of residential units if more correlated to the number of total units, compared with the relationship between the number of commercial units and the number of total units.

manhattan_corr2 <- manhattan_clean %>%
  mutate(`NEIGHBORHOOD` = as.factor(`NEIGHBORHOOD`))

correl <- cor(manhattan_corr2[sapply(manhattan_corr2, is.numeric)], use = "complete.obs")

round(correl, 3)

Analysis: ANOVA

To better conduct the predictive analysis, Neighborhood here is converted to factor.

manhattan_pred <- manhattan_clean %>%
  mutate(`NEIGHBORHOOD` = as.factor(`NEIGHBORHOOD`))

Four ANOVA tests are run to test the following answers.
1. Does there exist any significant difference in sale prices among properties in different neighborhoods?
2. Does there exist any significant difference in sale prices among different months of the year?
3. Does there exist any significant difference in sale price among different building classes?
4. Does there exist any significant difference in sale price among different tax classes at the time of sale?

Sale Prices and Neighborhood

To test the hypothesis of:
H0: There is no significant difference in sale prices among properties in different neighborhoods.
H1: There exist certain ignificant differences in sale prices among properties in different neighborhoods.

Result: As the p-value is extremely small, we could reject the null hypothesis and conclude that neighborhood really matters when it comes to the sale prices of properties.

mod1 <- aov(`SALE PRICE` ~ `NEIGHBORHOOD`, data = manhattan_pred)
summary(mod1)

## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Sale Prices and Sale Date (Month of the Year)

H1: There exist certain significant differences in sale prices among different months of the year.*

Result: As the p-value is large compared with the threshold value, we could not reject the null hypothesis and conclude that sale prices of properties do not differ among the different time periods of the year. The time series visualization generated previously could verify the result of this test as other than the two extreme peaks in Feburary and June, the sale prices flutuate pretty much within identical ranges.

Analysis: Linear Regression

Six linear regressions are conducted to answer the following questions:
1. Does sale price increase with the gross square feet?
2. Does sale price increase with the land square feet?
3. Does sale price decrease with the building age?
4. Does sale price increase with the number of commerical units?
5. Does sale price increase with the number of residential units?
6. Does sale price increase with the number of total units?

Sale Price and Gross Square Feet

To test the hypothesis of:
H1: Sale price increases with the increase of gross square feet.
H0: Gross square feet does not impact the sale price.

Results: As the p-value being extremely small and the t-value being high, we could reject the null hypothesis. And from the coefficient, we could see that there is a positive relationship that as gross square feet goes higher, the sale price goes higher.

Comparison of Land Square Feet and Gross Square Feets Impact on Sale Price

A unit of increase in land square feet would lead to a bigger unit of increase in sale price, compared with the result of a unit of increase in gross square feet. While for gross square feet, one unit of increase would lead to an increase of around 25 in sale price.

Conclusion

Given all information gathered from the analyses, the sale price of a certain property in Manhattan is a complicated issue to look at, as it is influenced by a bunch of variables, simultaneously and towards different directions. Some interesting findings are:
1. As many people would think that there is a certain hot season for property sales while there is also a cold season - the time of the sale, when tested on a monthly basis, do not really align with the significant differences seen in the sale price. But two outstanding time periods are February and June, judged solely from the data of last year.
2. Many would think the gross square feet as the more critical predictor as compared with land square feet - because there are just so many high-rises across the Manhattan Island. However, the latter actually has a bigger influence on the final sale prices of properties.
3. The ages of buildings do not have significant impact on the sale price. This might appear counter-intuitive as Manhattan property market is one that truly values older buildings (a.k.a the pre-war ones). However, since the result delivers the message that building age does not influence the sale price as much as people would assume, this might be due to the fact that most of the truly old buildings are barely seen available on market. So the data set that this analysis is based on includes most of the buidlings that are more recently constructed.
4. It is interesting to find out that the number of commercial units has bigger impact on the sale price, as opposed to the impact from the number of total units and the number of residential units. This might be due to that the return on investment, ROI, from the commerical units are higher than the ROI from the residential units.
5. Tax class really does matter when it comes to the finalized sale price - perhaps it is because of tax class indicates information such as the building class category that a certain property falls under.

Limitation and Possible Improvement

One limitation is that this dataset is comparatively large and with quite a few variables depicting the observations from various aspects - some might consider this as an advantage though. Doing analysis based on a large dataset could make test results more robust. But it could also add on difficulties of finding detailed and intriguing patterns. Thus, focusing more on one specific area for the analysis would be more effective in some senses: what about an analysis on the property market in Chelsea neighborhood only? Or, what about an analysis on the residential properties only? Or, what about an analysis on the properties that were relatively more newly-built - say, something that was built after 2000.
Better conversions and management of the data could also be conducted in the pre-processing phase. For example, for variable Building Class Category, there are over 40 classes. Thus, finding a way to better organize these classes might do good to the analysis looking at the bigger picture.
Since the big conclusion is that the sale price could not be determined by solely one variable, buidling a predictive model that takes in all of those variables that matter would be the next step. Another area of improvement might be creating training dataset and test dataset for more in-depth study. And for models of this kind of complexity, certain test that helps with feature selection such as the LASSO test could be conducted.
